### STOP â€” production-DB schema drift surfaces during M2 audit

A read-only audit against the Neon `production` branch (
`ep-steep-bonus-aol2051y`, the endpoint stamped in `.env.production`
AND in `vercel env pull production`) returns a state that contradicts
the codebase migration history:

- `_prisma_migrations` tracking table **does not exist** on the prod
  branch. So Prisma never recorded a migration as applied there.
- `MatchEvent` columns present: `id, matchId, kind, goalType,
  scorerId, assisterId, minute, createdById, createdAt, updatedAt`.
  Missing: `beneficiaryTeamId` (added in v1.82.0 by
  `20260515000000_match_event_beneficiary`).
- `PlayerLeagueAssignment` columns present: `id, playerId,
  leagueTeamId, fromGameWeek, toGameWeek, createdAt, onboardingStatus,
  joinSource`. Missing: `applicationStatus`, `position`, `positions`,
  `preferredPositions`, `secondaryPositions`, `comments`, `idShared`,
  `pictureUrl`, `name`, etc. (all added in v1.65.x â†’ v1.86.0).
- `League` columns present: `id, name, location, startDate, endDate,
  createdAt, updatedAt, description, subdomain`. Missing every column
  added in v1.5x â†’ v1.86.0 (recruiting, visibility, ballType,
  playerFormat, abbreviation, defaultLeague pointer, etc.).
- Live website `https://t9l.me/id/minato-2025` returns the
  `NEXT_HTTP_ERROR_FALLBACK;404` template â€” consistent with a
  schema-mismatch crash falling back to a stub page.
- The version footer `https://t9l.me/` shows `v1.85.5` â€” but the
  v1.85.x feature surface depends on schema columns that don't exist
  on the connected DB.

**Even more confusing:** an EARLIER read (within this same session,
~15 min before this audit) against the same connection string returned
5 Guest pseudo-players + 3 MatchEvents with non-null
`beneficiaryTeamId` selectable â€” the schema state I needed.
Re-running the audit with raw SQL now confirms 0 guests + the
beneficiary column missing. Something restored or replaced the
`production` branch state in between, OR the connection string is now
landing on a different physical compute endpoint than it did earlier.

### Why this stops M2

The migration's data-backfill UPDATE references
`me."beneficiaryTeamId"`. If the column doesn't exist on the prod DB
at deploy time, the entire migration aborts mid-run, leaving the new
boolean columns added but the Guest cleanup not applied â€” a partial
state that's harder to roll back than either extreme.

Two possible explanations the operator can resolve:

1. **The `_prisma_migrations` chain has been broken for weeks** and
   the next `prisma migrate deploy` on prod will need to apply ALL
   32 migrations in sequence. In that case, my migration sits at the
   end of the chain and works correctly because every prior migration
   runs first. But it also means the deploy is high-risk: 32 unapplied
   migrations including v1.84.0's `LeagueVisibility` enum + `User.defaultLeagueId`
   FK + `PlayerLeagueAssignment.preferredPositions[]` array + many
   data-shape changes the live site already expects. We'd want a Neon
   snapshot first and a careful per-migration sanity check.

2. **The connection string in `.env.production` / Vercel env is
   stale** and the actual live prod DB is at a different Neon endpoint
   that DOES have the recent migrations applied. In that case the
   audit numbers I recorded for M1 (5 guests + 3 events) reflect the
   "real" prod state, and my migration would compose cleanly. We'd
   want to find the live endpoint, re-confirm the audit, and proceed.

### Hard constraints invoked

Per CLAUDE.md "Plan-then-ship" stop conditions:
- "data destruction" â€” the migration deletes 5 Player rows + 4 PLM
  rows; user authorized this against the *seeded* Guest pseudo-players,
  but the prod-DB I can audit doesn't even contain those rows in the
  shape M1 documented. Authorization was for a known data shape.
- "schema irreversibility" â€” `DROP NOT NULL` is additive, but the FK
  rebuild + the conditional data backfill against a column that may
  not exist is not.
- "ambiguity that's actually a product decision" â€” operator needs to
  decide which state is canonical before any migration ships.

Per CLAUDE.md Layer 3 (Neon snapshot) on a non-additive PR: snapshot
required before merge. The Neon free-tier branch limit (10) is
currently hit; `neonctl branches create` returns "branches limit
exceeded" and `neonctl branches delete` is in the agent's deny list.
An operator would need to either retire an old `pre-pr-N-<slug>` /
`preview/feat/migration-*` branch OR confirm the additive-only path
without a snapshot.

### Surfaced for operator decision; M3-M5 paused

The migration files are written and committed locally to the worktree
but NOT pushed. Schema edits to `prisma/schema.prisma` and the new
migration directory under `prisma/migrations/` are the only changes so
far. Awaiting operator guidance on:

1. Which Neon endpoint reflects "live prod" today.
2. Whether to retire one of the existing Neon branches to free a slot
   for a v1.87.0 pre-PR snapshot.
3. Whether to proceed assuming `prisma migrate deploy` will catch up
   the entire chain on next deploy (rolling forward from a much-older
   schema state).

## M2 (resumed) â€” operator confirmed v1.86.0 incident resolved

Operator clarified: the prod-DB drift I observed was the v1.86.0 failed
deploy window â€” `20260510000000_plm_preferred_secondary_positions` shipped
with `"PlayerLeagueMembership"` (Prisma model name) instead of
`"PlayerLeagueAssignment"` (the @@map'd SQL table name). v1.86.1 hotfix
corrected the SQL; v1.87.0 (per-league player retirement) merged
cleanly post-fix. Worktree rebased onto `origin/main` at v1.87.0
(commit `3a44f19`). Version bumped to v1.88.0.

New CLAUDE.md rule + post-mortem at
[docs/migration-sql-lessons.md](docs/migration-sql-lessons.md):
- Never hand-author migration SQL â€” always
  `prisma migrate dev --create-only`.
- Migrations should not contain `DROP TABLE`, `TRUNCATE`, or
  `DELETE FROM` outside the bootstrap `new_schema` migration.
- `UPDATE` / `INSERT` are permitted exceptions, but table names must
  use the `@@map` name.

### Migration regenerated and split

- Schema changes regenerated via
  `npx prisma migrate diff --from-schema-datamodel <prev> --to-schema-datamodel <new> --script`
  (Prisma-authored SQL, identical to what `migrate dev --create-only`
  would emit). Output verified to reference only `MatchEvent` (no
  `@@map` model in scope).
- UPDATE backfills hand-authored but use the `@@map` name
  `"PlayerLeagueAssignment"` per the post-mortem checklist (verified
  by grepping `@@map` in `prisma/schema.prisma`: only
  `PlayerLeagueMembership @@map("PlayerLeagueAssignment")` matters
  for this migration).
- DESTRUCTIVE deletion of seeded Guest Player + PLM rows MOVED OUT of
  the migration into a separate operator-run script
  [scripts/v188CleanupGuestPseudoPlayers.ts](scripts/v188CleanupGuestPseudoPlayers.ts).
  --dry-run by default, --apply gated behind two safety checks:
  (a) `MatchEvent.isGuestScorer` column must exist (i.e. migration
  applied), (b) no `MatchEvent.scorerId` / `assisterId` may still
  point at a guest playerId (i.e. UPDATE backfill ran).
- Migration directory renamed to
  `20260519000000_match_event_guest_flags` to avoid date collision
  with v1.87.0's `20260518000000_plm_retired_at`.

